  "doc_id": "38320",
  "text": "Shock also affected other behaviors, including a reduction ot daily running in a wheel in rats by both escapable and inescapable shock. This finding is opposite that for shock-induced analgesia, which occurs only after inescapable shock, perhaps because the daily running is not a part of the fear response, but analgesia is. Regardless, naltrexone did not alter the suppression of running by shock, indicating that it is probably an opiate effect [CITATION_1] . Another response to shock is an increase in self-administration of opiates in rats. Lever pressing for access to a fentanyl solution sped up after shock, and when water or quinine (which has a similar taste to fentanyl) was substituted for the agonist, extinction occurred [CITATION_2] , indicating that opiate actions were involved in the change, with stress-released endogenous opiates potentiating the exogenous one.",
  "correct_citation": {
